      <body>
         <p>Dear Sir,</p>
         <p>Herewith I send you a Requisition which a few of your friends here have got up for you. It is but a simple and humble production but I believe it to be truly sincere and on that account I am sure you will esteem it — you will <sic>purceive</sic> it is not intended for publication. Indeed I am well aware that many who have signed it [w]ould feel hurt by their names appearing, in any shape, in  a public way. But at <supplied reason="omitted-in-text">the</supplied> same time the Requisition itself might be published (without the names) in any of your hand-bills if thought necessary.— I have seen <persName ref="prsn:Alla01">Mr Allason</persName> about the <placeName ref="plc:Sund01">Long Room Arcade</placeName>. He will accommodate you upon the same term as before. I pushed him sore for an abatement but could not succeed. He promises however, in case of a failure to share the loss with you. — I have made an apology to <persName ref="prsn:Houg01">Mr. Houghton</persName> for you with which he was quite satisfied and bids me inform you that he will be very glad to see you when you come here again. I hope you keep clear of cold and enjoy good health. My <persName ref="prsn:Marl02">wife</persName> and <persName ref="prsn:Marl03">son</persName> desire to be kindly remembered to you ; as also do <persName ref="prsn:Ward01">Mr Wardropper</persName>[?] and many others. Hoping to see you soon, I remain,</p>
         <p>Dear sir,</p> <p>yours truly</p> 
         <p>J Marley</p>
         
         <p>[[2]] To Mr Thos Morrison Senr - Dunfermline</p>
         <p><placeName ref="tgn:7017245">Sunderland</placeName> Oct 10th 1836</p>
         
         <p>We the undersigned having been highly gratified by the able manner in which Mr Morrison delivered his course of Lectures on the Morrisonian system of Astronomy: and being desirous that he should deliver a course of Lectures on Political oeconomy in this town, do respectfully invite him to do so at his earliest convenience.</p>
